 to reach the resting potential\n (as elluded to my @MCM in the comments).<\/p>\n\n<p>There are some great animations demonstrating this principal on the <a href=\"http://www.bris.ac.uk/synaptic/basics/basics-2.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">University of Bristol's website<\/a>. They clearly shows how positive charge can be conferred over the membrane.<\/p>\n\n<p>A (<em>now deleted<\/em>) comment linked to the below image that shows the potential and when the gates are opened and closed. I would still go to the bristol website too to see it in action, but this figure is a quick go to once you get your head around the timing of ion flux.<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/Y0C3i.gif\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n\n<p>As with most biology, it is a little more complicated than that overly simple model. There are entire books on how neurons control their charges.<\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p><strong><em>Note<\/em>:<\/strong> The key terminology is somewhat muddled and there doesn't seem to be a standard term. I have seen this \"recovery\" phase called <strong>undershoot<\/strong>, <strong>overshoot<\/strong> (and overshoot rather unhelpfully also refers to another part of the action potential), <strong>the refractory period<\/strong>, and discussed as <strong>part of hyperpolarization<\/strong>. The go to term is <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Afterhyperpolarization\" rel=\"nofollow\"><strong>afterpolarisation<\/strong><\/a> if you want to research this more thoroughly.<\/p>\n","answer_id":34222,"question_id":34215,"up_vote_count":6,"last_edit_date":1448534282}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/34215/what-recovers-normal-polarisation-after-hyperpolarisation","last_activity_date":1448534282,"creation_date":1431526385,"answer_count":1,"title":"What recovers normal polarisation after hyperpolarisation?","body":"<p>I have been taught that a Na+/K+ pump helps to recover normal polarisation after hyperpolarisation in neurons. I could not find out how it does that, since I've also been taught that such a pump moves 3 Na+ out of the cell and 2 K+ into the cell. That implies that the potential can only get more negative. How does this work?<\/p>\n\n<p>My hypothesis was that the potential 'leaks' out and recovers the 70 mV that way. I couldn't verify that, however.<\/p>\n","question_id":34215,"tags":["neuroscience","cell-membrane","action-potential"],"score":6,"accepted_answer_id":34222,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":118,"up_vote_count":6,"last_edit_date":1431565113},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4e608c12d1eca9db185f095b116cee46?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":20302,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20302/benjamin-philion","reputation":1,"display_name":"Benjamin Philion"},"closed_date":1448557242,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":0,"post_id":41013,"edited":false,"creation_date":1448513620,"comment_id":69352,"body":"If the cells that make up your sperm over the past 40 years accrued mutations, assuming you weren&#39;t already born with some, can carry mutations. That doesn&#39;t meant that the mutations have necessarily occurred within essential genes, or that the mutations lead to deleterious results, but it will definitely not be exactly the same as the DNA that was in the sperm and the egg that was fertilized to make you. As for your partner, her eggs were produced when she was in her mother&#39;s uterus, before she was born. They lay dormant until she starts to ovulate, so they won&#39;t have accrued that many."}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41013/how-can-my-baby-dna-be-brand-new","last_activity_date":1448512900,"creation_date":1448512900,"answer_count":0,"title":"How can my baby DNA be \"brand n