gene happens to be in turn an activator of many downstream genes, then efficient control actually helps in saving the cellular resources. I can't cite any literature for it but I have observed this in one of my unpublished research work using mathematical models. <\/li>\n<\/ol>\n","answer_id":40936,"question_id":40912,"up_vote_count":5,"last_edit_date":1448397287}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/40912/why-does-a-cell-produce-a-lot-of-p53-protein-only-to-later-degrade-it","last_activity_date":1448397287,"creation_date":1448291576,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why does a cell produce a lot of p53 protein only to later degrade it?","body":"<p>It is known that the half life of p53 is short and so does that play a role in the amount of energy the cell would need to expend to degrade all the p53? By that does the fact that the half life of p53 is so short does that just allow for the cell to not have to expend very much energy to degrade the p53 so in a way the cell doesn't \"mind\" having to degrade the p53 since it wouldn't take a lot of effort? <\/p>\n","question_id":40912,"tags":["cell-biology"],"score":3,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":47,"up_vote_count":3},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://graph.facebook.com/1700046893564658/picture?type=large","user_type":"registered","user_id":20275,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20275/zaigham-awan","reputation":6,"display_name":"Zaigham Awan"},"closed_date":1448396868,"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://graph.facebook.com/724354877676809/picture?type=large","user_type":"registered","user_id":17473,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17473/sunboyharry","reputation":139,"display_name":"sunboyharry"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1448391440,"creation_date":1448391440,"body":"<p>You are confused among DNA replication, DNA transcrption, and RNA translation.<\/p>\n\n<p>First, DNA replication happens during cell division, it create two exactly same daughter DNA.<\/p>\n\n<p>Second, DNA transcription transcribes DNA sequence into RNA sequence, this RNA sequence may be used to synthesize protein, or RNA itself as signal, etc.<\/p>\n\n<p>Third, RNA translation is the RNA sequence (codon) recognized by tRNA, and then synthesize protein sequence.<\/p>\n\n<p>AUG is a codon in the RNA, the is recognized by tRNA, and then start translation. And please remember, DNA use A, G, C, T, but RNA use A, G, C, U, there is no <strong>U<\/strong> in DNA. <\/p>\n\n<p>For DNA synthesis, why does it need primer? I have another answer for solving your question: <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/a/40954/17473\">http://biology.stackexchange.com/a/40954/17473<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":40955,"question_id":40953,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/40953/why-dna-polymerase-3-requires-a-primer-for-replication","last_activity_date":1448391440,"creation_date":1448389994,"answer_count":1,"title":"why dna polymerase 3 requires a primer for replication","body":"<p>Why DNA polymerase 3 needs a primer to star replication.And whats happens when there is no AUG sequence on entire DNA.<\/p>\n","question_id":40953,"tags":["cell-biology","dna","dna-sequencing","human-genome"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":1,"closed_reason":"duplicate","is_answered":true,"view_count":32,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5b5440c34109e218b55c29d2450159ee?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6136,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6136/21joanna12","reputation":659,"display_name":"21joanna12","accept_rate":46},"closed_date":1448396824,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":40948,"edited":false,"creation