/35776/how-does-the-platypus-grow-before-it-eats","last_activity_date":1448377874,"creation_date":1436043593,"answer_count":1,"title":"How does the Platypus grow before it eats?","body":"<p>From <a href=\"https://youtu.be/NGuIezLFidY?t=16m45s\">this fascinating documentary on monotremes<\/a> it is mentioned that the Platypus is born less than 1 cm in length, but has doubled its size by day three when it begins to nurse. <strong>How does the animal grow before feeding?<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>Surely by <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conservation_of_mass\">conservation of mass<\/a> there must be some alternate process by which materials are being processed and absorbed by the young animal. Does it absorb nutrients from the air or surrounding environment? Sucking on dirt? Osmosis?<\/p>\n","question_id":35776,"tags":["reproduction","mammals"],"score":5,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":62,"up_vote_count":5},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5b5440c34109e218b55c29d2450159ee?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6136,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6136/21joanna12","reputation":659,"display_name":"21joanna12","accept_rate":46},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/uonSZ.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15272,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15272/lightweaver","reputation":740,"display_name":"lightweaver","accept_rate":43},"score":5,"post_id":40840,"edited":false,"creation_date":1448108200,"comment_id":69063,"body":"In biology, ligands are chemicals that attach to receptors on cell membranes, stimulating a cellular response. You\u2019re using the definition of a ligand in chemistry. :)"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":2,"post_id":40840,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/uonSZ.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15272,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15272/lightweaver","reputation":740,"display_name":"lightweaver","accept_rate":43},"edited":false,"creation_date":1448108807,"comment_id":69065,"body":"@lightweaver - that&#39;s sufficient for an answer when you include a link to the respective definitions."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-uS0Elf7lRBo/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAE8/R5J8cBgSOg8/photo.jpg?sz=128","user_type":"registered","user_id":16299,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16299/vance-l-albaugh","reputation":1284,"display_name":"Vance L Albaugh"},"score":5,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1448377528,"creation_date":1448377528,"body":"<p>The definition of \"ligand\" in the question, \"a molecule or ion which donates a pair of electrons to a central transition metal ion in a complex\" is clearly a more technical 'chemistry-type' of definition. Ligands in biology and medicine can be all sorts of molecules, though most of the time we think of them as molecules that bind to a particular receptor. Those receptors can be <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ion_channel\">ion channels<\/a>, <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Enzyme\">enzymes<\/a>, <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transmembrane_protein\">transmembrane receptors<\/a> at the cell surface or within the cell in an organelle, nuclear proteins that control expression of genes in the cell nucleus (i.e. <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transcription_factor\">transcription factors<\/a>), etc...the list could go on and on... In fact, more recently we have come to appreciate that compounds like <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bile_acid\">bile acids<\/a> - that were previously thought to be important only in fat absorption in the gastrointestinal/digestive tract - are also ligands for receptors that control gene transcription (<a href=\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1097276500803482\">\"Farnesoid X Receptor\"<\/a>) as well as increase energy expenditure in brown adipose tissue and skeletal muscle (through receptors like the <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16400329\">\"TGR5\"<\/a> receptor).<\/p>\n\n<p>But... back to the question...<\/p>\n\n<p>If a molecule binds to a receptor, then it's a ligand for that receptor. The ligand doesn't have to donate any electrons specifically to a transition metal. Most of the time in medicine/biology the binding of a specific ligand to its receptor is a reversible process that is dependent on the concentration of the ligand and the availability of the receptor (among other things). The specificity of ligand for the receptor is due to chemical factors like hydrogen bonding, electrostatic interactions (like positive charges attracting negative charges), as well as other chemical interactions beyond the scope of this question. As you can see from the picture below, the hydroxy groups (-OH) that are part of the serine residues on the receptor are hydrogen bonding with the hydroxy groups on the epinephrine molecule itself. Moreover, the carboxy group (-COOH) on the aspartate residue is binding to the positively charged amino (NH3+) on the epinephrine molecule.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/i7Fp7.gif\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/i7Fp7.gif\" alt=\"Adrenaline (aka epinephrine) binding to its receptor - the adrenergic receptor\"><\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":40945,"question_id":40840,"up_vote_count":5}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/40840/how-is-adrenaline-a-ligand","last_activity_date":1448377528,"creation_date":1448107214,"answer_count":1,"title":"How is adrenaline a ligand?","body":"<p>I keep reading that adrenaline is a ligand, however from what I understand a ligand is a molecule or ion which donates a pair of electrons to a central transition metal ion in a complex. How then is adrenaline a ligand?<\/p>\n\n<p>Thank you for your help :)<\/p>\n","question_id":40840,"tags":["biochemistry","molecular-biology","endocrinology","receptor"],"score":5,"accepted_answer_id":40945,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":119,"up_vote_count":5},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/Zl6dm.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":13496,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13496/cdb","reputation":1164,"display_name":"CDB","accept_rate":100},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/56b4833d86d3cccc3ccfd6eeaf0b767e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14946,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14946/mdperry","reputation":2645,"display_name":"mdperry"},"score":3,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0d7c5cbd0c2f965a3712ff687c53f997?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14552,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14552/aaaaaa","reputation":2058,"display_name":"aaaaaa"},"score":4,"post_id":31493,"edited":false,"creation_date":1429424526,"comment_id":52770,"body":"and also epigenetic factors, just look on recent Nature paper, memory can be transferred without change in genetic code <i>per se<\/i>: <a href=\"http://www.nature.com/news/fearful-memories-haunt-mouse-descendants-1.14272\" rel=\"nofollow\">nature.com/news/&hellip;<\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":31493,"edited":false,"creation_date":1448371448,"comment_id":69233,"body":"Please try adding some explanation along with citations for how instincts are hard-wired. What you are essentially talking about is the physiological mechanism whereas the actual question appears to be about the genetic basis."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1429434576,"creation_date":1429408045,"body":"<p>This stuff is hard-wired into either the organism's nervous system, or endocrine signalling pathways (e.g., hormones), or possibly a combination of those two mechanisms.  In that sense, yes it is encoded in the genome, but not in a language that we can understand or interpret yet. Also, don't overlook all of the macromolecules that the female provides to the developing egg during oogenesis, your mother gave you lots of things besides a copy of her genome--you just don't have any of those macromolecules left now--but you wouldn't be here without them.<\/p>\n","answer_id":31493,"question_id":31459,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1429434576}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/31459/how-is-instinct-carried-from-one-generation-to-another","last_activity_date":1448371494,"creation_date":1429318033,"answer_count":1,"title":"How is instinct carried from one generation to another?","body":"<p>How can non-structural information, specifically instinct (a fixed pattern of behavior that an organism reverts to as a response to certain stimuli), be passed on from generation to generation (such as an unborn baby's instinct to begin inhaling and exhaling amniotic fluid while still in the mother's womb to \"practice\" breathing, a sea turtle's inclination to enter the sea after hatching, etc.)?<\/p>\n\n<p>Does DNA have anything to do with it? I can't imagine what else it could be, considering that the genome is the only thing an organism passes on to it's progeny.<\/p>\n","question_id":31459,"tags":["behaviour"],"score":2,"accepted_answer_id":31493,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":65,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1448371494},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-qWL_6LUuIoI/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAz8/Hxqz8IIlzGg/photo.jpg?sz=128","user_type":"registered","user_i