>Hepatic disease<\/em> can be be caused by problems outside of the liver as such, e.g. blockage in the hepatic vein.<\/p><\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>Users more knowledgeable in medicine are welcome to fill in or correct me if I'm mistaken.<\/p>\n","answer_id":31395,"question_id":31254,"up_vote_count":12,"last_edit_date":1448271222}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/31254/why-do-people-in-the-scientific-community-use-terminology-such-as-renal-hepatic","last_activity_date":1448272845,"creation_date":1428780874,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why do people in the scientific community use terminology such as renal, hepatic, cardiac instead of kidney, liver and heart?","body":"<p>Are there differences between <em>renal, hepatic, cardiac<\/em> and <em>kidney, liver and heart<\/em>? Is the \"jargon\" used more commonly because of tradition, or is there some definitive biological basis to it?<\/p>\n","question_id":31254,"tags":["human-biology","physiology","medicine","nomenclature","general-biology"],"score":4,"accepted_answer_id":31395,"down_vote_count":1,"closed_reason":"off-topic","is_answered":true,"view_count":155,"up_vote_count":5,"last_edit_date":1448272845},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/OxfyD.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3059,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3059/dd3","reputation":2303,"display_name":"dd3","accept_rate":95},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/LnfsA.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3061,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3061/yummyclaypot","reputation":575,"display_name":"yummyclaypot"},"score":1,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1362476490,"creation_date":1362453379,"body":"<p>Excess thymidine in a mitotic cell generates negative feedback on the production of deoxycytidine triphosphate from cytidine-5'-phosphate. Excess quantities of deoxyadenosine and deoxyguanosine <em>also<\/em> block progression through S-phase. However, as a reagent for the control of replication timing, thymidine has been found to work best as its blocking activity can be applied and reversed more consistently.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://dx.doi.org/10.1038/194682a0\" rel=\"nofollow\">Xeros N. (1962) <em>Deoxyriboside Control and Synchronization of Mitosis.<\/em> Nature 194: 682-683.<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":7441,"question_id":7440,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1362476490}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/7440/how-does-a-thymidine-block-halt-dna-synthesis","last_activity_date":1448257900,"creation_date":1362448430,"answer_count":1,"title":"How does a thymidine block halt DNA synthesis?","body":"<p>The best I've been able to find is that there's a feedback mechanism, but what is this feedback, and how does the mechanism work? If it's just that the concentration of thymidine is too high, why won't excess quantities of other nucleotides do the same thing? (Or do they, and I don't know about it?)<\/p>\n","question_id":7440,"tags":["dna","replication"],"score":2,"accepted_answer_id":7441,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":5705,"up_vote_count":2},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://graph.facebook.com/1085183699/picture?type=large","user_type":"registered","user_id":20204,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20204/hadi-hassan","reputation":119,"display_name":"Hadi Hassan"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":0,"post_id":40835,"edited":false,"creation_date":1448096909,"comment_id":69056,"body":"Welcome to Bio. It&#39;s best to ask one specific targeted question per post. I.e.  You might want to split them up. Second, a ribosome is huge. There&#39;s many things that gives it functionality. There is not something as <i>the thing<\/i