ctually helps."}],"down_vote_count":1,"last_activity_date":1448223897,"creation_date":1448223897,"body":"<p>I think the use of drugs for simple things like a blood draw should be a last resort. Having a cup of tea or two can work wonders at raising your blood volume and making the blood draw easier.<\/p>\n\n<p>A nitroglycerin tablet would risk systemic side effects in many patients, so a topical ointment could be used to minimize these effects. Nitroglycerin has been applied topically over the venipuncture site to cause a transient vasodilation, and potentially make the blood draw easier. There are varying reports on its efficacy - <a href=\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0196064487806820\" rel=\"nofollow\">Hecker et al. (1983)<\/a> found nitroglycerin ointment helped venipuncture, <a href=\"http://journals.lww.com/nursingresearchonline/Abstract/1994/07000/Evaluation_of_the_Safety_and_Efficacy_Of_Topical.3.aspx\" rel=\"nofollow\">Griffith et al. (1994)<\/a> found it made no difference in vein size.<\/p>\n","answer_id":40891,"question_id":40887,"up_vote_count":3},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-uS0Elf7lRBo/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAE8/R5J8cBgSOg8/photo.jpg?sz=128","user_type":"registered","user_id":16299,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16299/vance-l-albaugh","reputation":1284,"display_name":"Vance L Albaugh"},"score":4,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1448252634,"creation_date":1448252634,"body":"<p>When we need to collect blood from patients we typically draw blood from peripheral veins that are superficial. These are the veins that you can see in some individuals hands and forearms. There are superficial leg veins that are visible. Drugs like nitroglycerin or other vasodilators do not have significant effects on the superficial veins that you'd be trying to withdrawal blood from in the extremities (i.e. arms and legs).  <\/p>\n\n<p>If you wanted to really engorge someone's veins, you'd likely have to load them up with intravenous fluids. However, this would not be safe in patients needing routine blood draws; especially elderly people who might become fluid-overloaded to the point at which the develop <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heart_failure\" rel=\"nofollow\">congestive heart failure<\/a>. Younger patients might temporarily have minimal increases in their circulating blood volume, but their kidneys would very quickly eliminate the excess fluid as urine.<\/p>\n","answer_id":40899,"question_id":40887,"up_vote_count":4}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/40887/blood-draw-from-the-elderly-or-those-with-tiny-veins","last_activity_date":1448252634,"creation_date":1448220492,"answer_count":2,"title":"Blood draw from the elderly or those with tiny veins","body":"<p>A lot of people have very small veins making it next to impossible to draw blood. <\/p>\n\n<p>Would a nitroglycerin tablet (or some other vasodilator) before drawing blood help to enlarge veins?<\/p>\n","question_id":40887,"tags":["human-biology","pharmacology","hematology","medicine"],"score":2,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":93,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1448226366},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/22a5cc617809fed3c309300a28e8adc4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":11829,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/11829/falsum","reputation":432,"display_name":"falsum","accept_rate":78},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":0,"post_id":40886,"edited":false,"creation_date":1448226740,"comment_id":69159,"body":"To make sure I understand your interpretation, does it involves that 1) $r_1+r_2=1$, 2) if $r_1=r_2$, then individuals interact randomly without preference, 3) If $r_1&gt;r_2$, then individuals interact preferentially when individuals playing the same strategy and 4) if $r_1&lt;r_2$, then individuals interact preferentially with individuals playing a different strategy? If the above is true I would expect the mean fitness in the population to be $\\frac{1}{2 (x+y)(r_1x+r_2y)}$ while the equation suggests that the mean fitness is $r_1x+r_2y$."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/22a5cc617809fed3c309300a28e8adc4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":11829,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/11829/falsum","reputation":432,"display_name":"falsum","accept_rate":78},"score":0,"post_id":40886,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"edited":false,"creation_date":1448249864,"comment_id":69177,"body":"@Remi.b 1). Yes, if my interpretation is correct. 2). Yes. 3 and 4) Here is a quote from the paper &quot;If r1 &gt; r2 and r3 &gt; r2, then players prefer to interact with their own kind. If, however, r1 &lt; r2 and r3 &lt; r2, then mixed interactions (between A and B) are more likely.&quot;"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/22a5cc617809fed3c309300a28e8adc4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":11829,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/11829/falsum","reputation":432,"display_name":"falsum","accept_rate":78},"score":0,"post_id":40886,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"edited":false,"creation_date":1448250609,"comment_id":69178,"body":"@Remi.b Note that I added a formula for $f_B$ to make my question more clear."}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/40886/games-with-non-uniform-interaction-rates","last_activity_date":1448250536,"creation_date":1448219940,"answer_count":0,"title":"Games with non-uniform interaction rates","body":"<p><strong>Background:<\/strong> \nMany models in evolutionary game theory assume uniform interaction rates. For instance, consider the $2\\times 2$ game:\n\\begin{array}{l c c}\n    &amp; A &amp; B \\\\\n    A &amp; a &amp; b \\\\\n    B &amp; c &amp; d\n\\end{array}\nThe fitness of the strategy $A$ is $xa + yb$, where $x$ and $y$ are the frequencies of the strategies $A$ and $B$, respectively.<\/p>\n\n<p>Taylor and Nowak \"Evolutionary game dynamics with non-uniform interaction rates\" (<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2880897/\" rel=\"nofollow\">link to the paper<\/a>) rewrite the fitness function to allow for non-uniform interaction. In particular, the fitness of the strategy $A$ and $B$ become:\n\\begin{equation}\nf_{A} = \\frac{ar_{1}x + br_{2}y}{r_{1}x + r_{2}y}; \\quad f_{B} = \\frac{cr_{2}x + dr_{3}y}{r_{2}x + r_{3}y}\n\\end{equation}\nAccording to this model, ``[a]nalogous to a chemical reaction, an $A$ player interacts with another $A$ player with reaction rate $r_{1}$, an $A$ player and a $B$ player interact with reaction rate $r_{2}$, and a $B$ player interacts with another $B$ player with reaction rate $r_{3}$.\" (p.244). <\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Question<\/strong>: What would be an intuitive interpretation of $f_A$ and $f_B$ (as defined by Taylor and Nowak)? <\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p><strong>Further comments<\/strong>: When $r_1 = r_2$ and $r_2 = r_3$, we have the situation with uniform interaction. But I am not sure how to interpret the above fitness function for when $r_1 \\neq r_2$ (and $r_2 \\neq r_3$). I thought of interpreting $r_1$ and $r_2$ as the conditional probabilities $P(A\\mid A)$  and $P(A\\mid B)$. However, if I'm right about this, $f_A$ would have to be  $r_1 a + r_2 b$ instead. For this reason, I am under the impression that the $r$s should not be conditional probabilities. But if the $r$s are not conditional probabilities, what are they exactly?<\/p>\n","question_id":40886,"tags":["evolution","natural-selection","theoretical-biology","evolutionary-game-theory"],"score":3,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":35,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1448250536},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f5384ef0aa4badda1f41daf83aca68bb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":17488,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17488/mpg","reputation":38,"display_name":"MPG","accept_rate":25},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/0la1I.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4833,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4833/dexter","reputation":1808,"display_name":"Dexter"},"score":0,"post_id":40863,"edited":false,"creation_date":1448189307,"comment_id":69129,"body":"What kinds of characteristics you are looking for ? I mean you can express successfully lot of animal proteins, pharmaceuticals and antigens into plant (<a href=\"http://www.nature.com/nrg/journal/v4/n10/full/nrg1177.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Julian KC 2003<\/a>). But I don&#39;t think they are any way important to plants."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f5384ef0aa4badda1f41daf83aca68bb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":17488,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17488/mpg","reputation":38,"display_name":"MPG","accept_rate":25},"score":1,"post_id":40865,"edited":false,"creation_date":1448164455,"comment_id":69107,"body":"Oh ok! That will be useful. Thanks!"}],"down_vote_count":