or metabolism, I think the response to heat is less well studied than the response to cold, but presumably metabolic rate (specifically, mitochondrial respiration) will <em>decrease<\/em> in order to reduce internal heat generation, in order to maintain body temperature. Again, these are homeostatic responses that occur <em>before<\/em> there is any marked change in body temperature. <a href=\"http://jeb.biologists.org/content/212/18/2885\" rel=\"nofollow\">Here is a review article<\/a> on these mechanisms.<\/p>\n\n<p>If you would expose the body to enough heat so that these normal responses cannot compensate, the body temperature will actually rise. Beyond 2-3 degrees (a normal fever), this is very dangerous because it will disturb a number of cellular processes. Cellular metabolism would certainly be affected, but mostly  because some enzymes have narrow temperature ranges where they can function; I don't think the actual heat energy of metabolites is an important factor here, but I don't know of any study on this. A variety of other proteins and cellular structures will be similarly affected. This will eventually affect key functions in the nervous and circulatory systems, which is life threatening. The <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperthermia\" rel=\"nofollow\">Wikipedia page on hyperthermia<\/a> is a good starting point for more information on this.<\/p>\n","answer_id":40873,"question_id":40868,"up_vote_count":2}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/40868/how-does-increased-heat-increase-the-rate-of-metabolism","last_activity_date":1448196483,"creation_date":1448171957,"answer_count":1,"title":"How does increased heat increase the rate of metabolism?","body":"<p>I have heard that taking a hot shower helps <\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>blood circulation <\/li>\n<li>metabolism. <\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>For (2) metabolism, I think that the rate is increased since kinetic energy is given to compound to bond with enzymes to react. Is this the only reason? In addition, why is (1) true?<\/p>\n","question_id":40868,"tags":["human-biology"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":30,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1448196483},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/NrrTz.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19263,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19263/notorious","reputation":41,"display_name":"notorious"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":1,"post_id":40867,"edited":false,"creation_date":1448216176,"comment_id":69145,"body":"Depolymerization of microtubules does occur at both ends, it is only that the kinetics are different at the plus-end than at the minus-end. Due to dynamic instability, depolymerization occurs about 100 times faster at the GDP end than the GTP end, but both will depolymerize, just at different rates."}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/40867/why-dont-the-minus-ends-of-microtubules-shrink","last_activity_date":1448188358,"creation_date":1448169797,"answer_count":0,"title":"Why don't the minus ends of microtubules shrink?","body":"<p>Is this because $\\alpha$-tubulin is always in the GTP state? Or is it because $\\gamma$-TuRC stabilizes the minus end?<\/p>\n","question_id":40867,"tags":["cell-biology"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":30,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1448188358},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/CGYSq.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16101,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16101/darwin-pc","reputation":211,"display_name":"Darwin PC"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f9bd7c0a93e1587d390866d374842b91?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9829,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9829/luigi","reputation":2475,"display_name":"Luigi"},"score":0,"post_id":34946,"edited":false,"creation_date":1433519022,"comment_id":56424,"body":"Can you cite a source for the classification you provided?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/CGYSq.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16101,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16101/darwin-pc","reputation":211,"display_name":"Darwin PC"},"score":0,"post_id":34946,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f9bd7c0a93e1587d390866d374842b91?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9829,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9829/luigi","reputation":2475,"display_name":"Luigi"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1433520633,"comment_id":56429,"body":"Here the citations, I couldn&#39;t put those in my question because at the moment my profile doesn&#39;t accept more than two links.   [1]: <a href=\"http://www.gettextbooks.com/isbn/9780824759049\" rel=\"nofollow\">gettextbooks.com/isbn/9780824759049<\/a>   [2]: <a href=\"http://msue.anr.msu.edu/news/knowing_nutrient_mobility_is_helpful_in_diagnosing_plant_nutrient_deficienc\" rel=\"nofollow\">msue.anr.msu.edu/news/&hellip;<\/a>   [3]: <a href=\"http://broome.soil.ncsu.edu/ssc012/Lecture/topic17.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">broome.soil.ncsu.edu/ssc012/Lecture/topic17.html<\/a>   [4]: <a href=\"http://lee.ifas.ufl.edu/Hort/Videos_and_Powerpoints/Presentation2013.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">lee.ifas.ufl.edu/Hort/Videos_and_Powerpoints/&hellip;<\/a>   [5]: <a href=\"http://nrcca.cals.cornell.edu/soilFertilityCA/CA1/CA1_print.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">nrcca.cals.cornell.edu/soilFertilityCA/CA1/CA1_print.html<\/a>"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2ad85f81981e5365a21d94114f3926b2?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":11657,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/11657/augurar","reputation":1124,"display_name":"augurar"},"score":2,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1433751881,"creation_date":1433751881,"body":"<h3>What does it mean for an element to be mobile or immobile in plants?<\/h3>\n\n<p>Generally speaking, mobile elements are those that can be moved from older to newer tissue in the plant, while immobile ones cannot be.  For example, calcium is incorporated into the cell wall, so it is immobile; it cannot be relocated later.<\/p>\n\n<p>Plants with a deficiency of mobile elements (<em>e.g.<\/em> nitrogen) will exhibit damage to older tissues as the nutrients are moved to new growth.  Conversely, plants lacking immobile elements (<em>e.g.<\/em> calcium) will exhibit stunted new growth while the older tissues stay healthy.  Some elements (<em>e.g.<\/em> sulphur) fall somewhere between these two extremes.<\/p>\n\n<p>To illustrate this concept, here is a plant with nitrogen deficiency (<a href=\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Spitskool_stikstofgebrek_(nitrogen_deficiency)_Brassica_oleracea_convar._capitata_var._alba.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\">source<\/a>).  Notice how the older leaves are dying while the newer leaves are relatively normal.<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/dhc3m.jpg\" alt=\"Brassica oleracea with nitrogen deficiency\"><\/p>\n\n<h3>Is there an official list of mobile and immobile elements?<\/h3>\n\n<p>No.  You will probably have to survey the literature yourself to come up with such a list.<\/p>\n\n<h3>Why are some elements not mentioned in the sources?<\/h3>\n\n<p>Elements like Pb or Sr do not appear in either list because plants generally do not use these elements at all.  Only a few elements are present in any appreciable quantity in plants.  The main elements used are C, H, O, P, K, N, S, Ca, Fe, and Mg. Additionally, some other elements such as Cu, Mo, Al, and Cl are used in trace amounts as enzymatic cofactors.  Si is used for structural purposes in some plants.<\/p>\n\n<p>However, even for \"useless\" elements, it is possible to study how these elements are absorbed transported through a given plant.  For instance, Rediske and Selders (1953) studied the absorption of strontium by bean plants using radioactive labeling, and concluded that the element was not relocated once absorbed by the plant.  This would make it an immobile element.<\/p>\n\n<h3>References<\/h3>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Feldman, Lewis J. (23 February 2015). <em><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rdancUsQb20&amp;t=32m20s\" rel=\"nofollow\">Water Relations, Mineral Nutrition, Fruit Development<\/a><\/em> (YouTube). Biology 1B. UC Berkeley. At 32:20.<\/li>\n<li>Lewis, Helen (9 January 2012). <a href=\"http://masteringhorticulture.blogspot.com/2012/01/mobile-vs-immobile-nutrients.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">\"Mobile vs Immobile Nutrients\"<\/a>. <em>Mastering Horticulture<\/em>.<\/li>\n<li>Rediske, J. H. and Selders, A. A. (October 1953). \"The Absorption and Translocation of Strontium by Plants\". <em>Plant Physiology<\/em> 28 (4): 594\u2013605. PMC <a href=\"https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC540423\" rel=\"nofollow\">540423<\/a>.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n","answer_id":35020,"question_id":34946,"up_vote_count":2}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/34946/which-are-mobile-and-immobile-elements-in-plants","last_activity_date":1448183071,"creation_date":1433518731,"answer_count":1,"title":"Which are mobile and immobile elements in plants?","body":"<p>I am confused with this element or nutrient classification in the plants, since some authors set elements like $\\ce{S}$ and $\\ce{Ni}$ as mobile and other as immobile elements (<a href=\"http://www.gettextbooks.com/isbn/9780824759049\" rel=\"nofollow\">Citation 1<\/a>, <a href=\"http://msue.anr.msu.edu/news/knowing_nutrient_mobility_is_helpful_in_diagnosing_plant_nutrient_deficienc\" rel=\"nofollow\">2<\/a>, <a href=\"http://broome.soil.ncsu.edu/ssc012/Lecture/topic17.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">3<\/a>, <a href=\"http://lee.ifas.ufl.edu/Hort/Videos_and_Powerpoints/Presentation2013.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">4<\/a>, <a href=\"http://nrcca.cals.cornell.edu/soilFertilityCA/CA1/CA1_print.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">5<\/a>). Then, I would like to know if there is a fixed and official classification.<\/p>\n\n<p>I found a classification only for those elements:<\/p>\n\n<p>Mobile: $\\ce{N}$, $\\ce{Mg}$, $\\ce{P}$, $\\ce{S}$, $\\ce{K}$, $\\ce{Ni}$<\/p>\n\n<p>Immobile: $\\ce{B}$, $\\ce{Ca}$, $\\ce{Mn}$, $\\ce{Fe}$, $\\ce{Co}$, $\\ce{Cu}$, $\\ce{Zn}$.<\/p>\n\n<p>And what about the rest of elements like $\\ce{Sr}$, $\\ce{Mo}$, $\\ce{Ba}$, $\\ce{Pb}$, etc?<\/p>\n","question_id":34946,"tags":["biochemistry","plant-physiology","nutrition"],"score":4,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":2165,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1433541406},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5bdf9f9c42649bc2b2f83200cc4f707d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":19899,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19899/makoto-kato","reputation":140,"display_name":"Makoto Kato"},"closed_date":1447875646,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"score":1,"post_id":40604,"edited":false,"creation_date":1447497759,"comment_id":68431,"body":"Where did you hear it?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/78GJV.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19650,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19650/yvide","reputation":1952,"display_name":"YviDe"},"score":5,"post_id":40604,"edited":false,"creation_date":1447498221,"comment_id":68433,"body":"Answered before searching the site. Might be a duplicate of    <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/q/884/19650\">biology.stackexchange.com/q/884/19650<\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.grava