s://www.gravatar.com/avatar/cabd5da7746d2afcf7be055d72907e67?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":10490,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/10490/noncom","reputation":281,"display_name":"noncom","accept_rate":40},"score":0,"post_id":40221,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"edited":false,"creation_date":1446729083,"comment_id":67776,"body":"@WYSIWYG Technically, you are right, the &quot;why&quot; of my question is probably answered in the referred duplicate, but there&#39;s more to it, and that &quot;more&quot; is being lost."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":40221,"edited":false,"creation_date":1446788156,"comment_id":67810,"body":"@noncom Okay. You can edit your question to focus on the &quot;more&quot; part; add more details so that it is no more yet another example of the CW question. We can have this reopened then."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/78GJV.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19650,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19650/yvide","reputation":1952,"display_name":"YviDe"},"score":4,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":40235,"edited":false,"creation_date":1446615148,"comment_id":67643,"body":"Penicillin is made by Penicillium, not Aspergillus."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1448087406,"creation_date":1446545576,"body":"<p>For a natural immunity to evolve, two things have to happen:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><p>The immunity has to actually occur. That means all the necessary mutations will need to be there to grant this bacterium resistance to penicillin. For penicillin, for example, bacteria that evolved such a resistance evolved to produce the enzyme beta-lactamase. <\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>The immunity has to grant an advantage. Penicillin is produced by <em>Penicillium<\/em>, which is a mold found in environments with lots of oxygen. Lots of bacterial species have never encountered penicillin and the vast majority (for example anaerobic bacteria that don't infect humans) never will. In the absence of this pressure, a resistance to penicillin, even if it evolves, will likely deteriorate within a few generations because the individuals with the resistance do not have an advantage in survival. Producing an enzyme such as beta-lactamase is not without its costs (protein synthesis). <\/p><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>While bacteria van exchange genetic material in the form of plasmids between different species, so not all species would need to evolve beta-lactamase de novo, this is also only \"helpful\" if the bacteria a) come in contact with resistant bacteria species, and b) if this resistance confers an advantage for the receiving species. <\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2937522/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Origins and Evolution of Antibiotic Resistance<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://archinte.jamanetwork.com/article.aspxhttp://archinte.jamanetwork.com/article.aspx?volume=151&amp;page=886\" rel=\"nofollow\">Mechanisms of Bacterial Resistance to Antibiotics<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":40235,"question_id":40221,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1448087406}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/40221/bacteria-resistance-to-natural-antibiotics","last_activity_date":1448087406,"creation_date":1446510761,"answer_count":1,"title":"Bacteria resistance to natural antibiotics?","body":"<p>It is a known fact that bacteria develop immunity to antibiotics. Why then did not all bacteria develop immunity to natural antibiotics like penicillin in the fungi?<\/p>\n\n<p>It is for sure that fungi did not care to continue killing all bacteria so that them won't be able to develop immunity (as we're adviced today to use antibiotics carefully, in order not to develop a superinfection)..<\/p>\n\n<p>Looking at all the time span that bacteria and fungi exist, it seems unlikely that there'd be any bacteria left not yet immune to penicillin at all. However, that's not the case, the antibiotic is still a rather successful one.<\/p>\n","question_id":40221,"tags":["bacteriology","antibiotics"],"score":4,"accepted_answer_id":40235,"down_vote_count":0,"closed_reason":"duplicate","is_answered":true,"view_count":70,"up_vote_count":4},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/KaVYs.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":17527,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17527/dshulgin","reputation":144,"display_name":"dshulgin","accept_rate":50},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":0,"post_id":40807,"edited":false,"creation_date":1448068047,"comment_id":69033,"body":"@MattDMo &#39;s answer is a great starting point. You probably also want to look through <b>Nature Reviews: Immunology<\/b> to get an overview of what is  currently occurring in the field today. From there, you can look at the referenced articles in more specialized journals for topics related to your project."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/476e67c92121154e7910301e56cdfc4c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":948,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/948/mattdmo","reputation":759