35370,"edited":false,"creation_date":1434821948,"comment_id":57574,"body":"@Armfoot: Yes, Wikipedia is sometimes wrong (and not just about this).  Likewise, the scientists who jumped on the &quot;birds are dinosaurs&quot; bandwagon for the sake of publicity are wrong.  As Remi.b says, it&#39;s to some extent a question of semantics, but the principle is that we group things that have similar characteristics under names.  Birds have characteristics that dinosaurs don&#39;t (adaptations for flight), just as mammals have characteristics (hair, milk glands) that reptiles don&#39;t, so we call them by different names."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":35370,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/de2c4fd753821f85c74d886aa17410de?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":107,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/107/kmm","reputation":8486,"display_name":"kmm"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1456993142,"comment_id":76171,"body":"@kmm birds are not reptiles. Sauropsids other than birds are generally considered as reptiles."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/de2c4fd753821f85c74d886aa17410de?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":107,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/107/kmm","reputation":8486,"display_name":"kmm"},"score":0,"post_id":35370,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"edited":false,"creation_date":1457013301,"comment_id":76202,"body":"@WYSIWYG No, birds are within the clade Reptilia, and thus are reptiles."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"