eps-show-a-clear-relationship","last_activity_date":1448043844,"creation_date":1448043844,"answer_count":0,"title":"Why doesn't EMG data for triceps show a clear relationship?","body":"<p>In a surface electromyography (EMG) experiment of the triceps muscle where a person lifts weights, I found the value for maximum amplitude of EMG signal to be rather similar for all loads of 0-10kg. The maximum amplitude was almost identical at 0kg and 10kg, and was greatest around 5kg. So this leads me to believe that the muscle activity within the triceps is only slightly affected by imposed load, meaning the triceps does not fatigue easily.<\/p>\n\n<p>Can someone confirm is there is some truth in this.<\/p>\n\n<p>(My results show a slight rise in muscle activity around 5kg, and then a continual decline until 10kg where experiment ceased) Why does this decline occur? Why doesn't the amplitude increase linearly with load?<\/p>\n","question_id":40818,"tags":["human-biology","physiology","muscles","human-physiology"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":27,"up_vote_count":0},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/33d04b3df6cfc22f6e75e33c5b0dc05a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":10379,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/10379/user36790","reputation":148,"display_name":"user36790","accept_rate":0},"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/40813/what-is-the-relation-between-chromomere-nucleosome","last_activity_date":1448035599,"creation_date":1448035599,"answer_count":0,"title":"What is the relation between chromomere & nucleosome?","body":"<p>I've been lately studying structure of chromosome where I got these two terms. I got many definitions of them.<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p><strong>Nucleosome:<\/strong> The basic structural sub-unit of chromatin, consisting of $\\sim 200$ base pairs of DNA &amp; an octamer of histone proteins.<\/p>\n  \n  <p><strong>Chromomere:<\/strong> Bead-like morphologically distinct structures of condensed nucleoprotein material occurring regularly at irregular intervals of chromonema thread.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>But in another book, I read:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Chromomeres are actually superposed coils of <strong>nucleosome<\/strong> bodies present linearly in the chromatid.<\/p>\n  \n  <p>[...] Under electron microscope chromatin is found to consist of <strong>bead like repeating structures<\/strong> known as nucleosome with $200$ base pairs of DNA surrounding an octamer of histone proteins &amp; one $\\mathsf{H}_1$ histone at outer part. <\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>So, both are <strong>bead-like structures<\/strong>; the later definition tells chromomeres are made of <strong>nucleosomes<\/strong>.<\/p>\n\n<p>I am quite confused what chromomeres actually are &amp; how it is related to nucleosome.<\/p>\n\n<p>So, my questions are:<\/p>\n\n<p>$\\bullet$ Are nucleosomes &amp; chromomeres the same thing as they are attributed by <em>bead<\/em> in the defintions?<\/p>\n\n<p>$\\bullet$ How is chromomere related to nucleosome?<\/p>\n\n<p>Could anyone please explain their relationship with each other?<\/p>\n","question_id":40813,"tags":["chromosome"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":1,"is_answered":false,"view_count":85,"up_vote_count":1}]}